title: NFP Is Not A Game Changer For The Fed
text:
The for September was marginally weaker at 136K vs. the 145K expectation. However with the revision to August’s number from 130K to 168K, the overall headline number will be viewed as slightly better than expected. The itself should not sway the Fed in its decision to cut rates on October 30. The dropped to 3.5% in September from 3.7% in August.

That said, as Average Hourly Earnings (MoM) dropped from 0.4% in August 0.0% in September (vs. an expectation on 0.3%), it was a huge miss and will heighten the Fed’s awareness of a slowdown in inflation over the month. The FOMC meets again on October 30. In theory, lower inflation would lead to a lower , which would lead to more rate cuts.

Immediately after the data's release, the spiked higher – mostly likely a relief rally from 2900 to near 2020. Given all the poor data released this week, the market is content to have a number that is in-line or slightly better. The S&P 500 is closing in on the 50% retracement at 2925 from the Oct. 2 high to Thursday’s lows. Support is at today’s low of 2896.75. Next support is Thursday’s low at 2855.

Emini S&P 500

Source: Tradingview, FOREX.com, CME

also spiked after the data release, also possibly on a relief rally. However on the 4-hour chart, we can see that a double top has formed, with the neckline broken near 107.05. This breakdown has failed for the moment, as horizontal support was held at 106.68. However a break below this level may confirm the next move lower. To find the target for a double top, take the distance of the high to low between the 2 highs and add it to the breakdown point. The target in this case is near 105.45.

Source: Tradingview, FOREX.com
